        "paragraph_index": 4,
        "text": "## Chemistry Insights\n\nThe log β values increase systematically with ionic strength for all three species, reflecting the strong medium-dependence typical of chloride complexation — chloride is often part of the background electrolyte itself. The thermodynamic (I = 0) values are the largest (log β₁ = 1.98, log β₂ = 2.60, log β₃ = 2.40), consistent with extrapolation to zero ionic strength removing activity-coefficient effects. The positive ΔS values (28–71 J mol⁻¹ K⁻¹) indicate that complex formation is entropy-driven, as expected for the release of hydration-shell water molecules when Cl⁻ enters the inner coordination sphere of Cd²⁺. No ML₄ (CdCl₄²⁻) species is recorded in SRD-46 for this system, likely because it forms appreciably only at very high chloride concentrations.",
